lture of immediate gratification, leading to complacency and hampering long-term progress. Only economic disaster, military action, or the eruption of an angry underclass seem capable of changing the status quo. A groundbreaking critique, The Culture of Contentment shows how the complacent majority captures the political process and determines economic policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFree enterprisezUnited States. 0aFree enterprise; United States. 0aPoorzUnited States. 0aPoor; United States. 0aSocial values. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aAdam Smith.  aCommunism.  aContented Electoral Majority.  aContented Majority.  aDemocratic Party.  aEastern Europe.  aFranklin D. Roosevelt.  aNew Deal.  aRepublican Party.  aRonald Reagan.  aUnited States.  aWestern Europe.  aacquisitions.  aarms buildup.  abureaucracy.  abureaucratic syndrome.  acapitalism.  acommon purpose.  acommunism.  acomplacency.  aconsumers.  acontentment.  acorporations.  acosts.  acrime.  adefense spending.  ademocracy.  adepression.  aeconomic accommodation.  aeconomic advantage.  aeconomic discomfort.  aeconomic life.  aeconomic policies.  aeconomic power.  aeconomic well-being.  aeconomically advantaged.  aeconomics.  aeffective demand.  aelectoral politics.  aexternal authority.  afinancial devastation.  afiscal policy.  aforeign policy.  afunctional underclass.  agovernment.  ahave nots.  ahaves.  aimmediate gratification.  aimmigrants.  aincomes.  aindustrial economy.  ainflation.  ainner cities.  ainternational relations.  alaissez faire.  aloan scandal.  amacroeconomic policy.  amacroeconomic regulation.  amedia.  amergers.  amiddle-class voting.  amilitary action.  amilitary powe